{
  "texts": [
    "If f (x) = y, the predictor f predicts the label correctly, otherwise, it makes a mistake.",
    "In order to quantify how serious a mistake is, we usually measure it by a loss function.",
    "In these notes, a loss function can be any function ℓ: Y 2 → [0, +∞) such that ℓ(y, y) = 0 for any y ∈ Y; ℓ(f (x), y) will be interpreted as the cost of the prediction error.",
    "In classification, the most natural loss function is:",
    "We will refer to it as the 0-1 loss function, and will use the following shorter notation: ℓ(y ′, y) = 1(y ̸ = y ′)."
  ]
}